reviewTitle: One was physically broken, the other was apparently spiritually broken…
reviewDescription: one star ratings are just too eye-catching and difficult to trust. Sometimes they are written in anger by someone who got burned. Sometimes they are written by a direct competitor trying to pad their own position. These are reasons why my experience with this product did not receive a one star rating.  My wife can be reckless with her things. Her Macbook Pro however has withstood years of abuse being on the road in suitcases and day-bags and just about any other parcel that you can imagine.  Recently she said to me that (after several years of use) her original white charging cord had finally given up and cashed it in. She asked if I would get her a replacement. Oh course I would, why wouldn’t I?  Off to Amazon I go. Do a quick search and a quick scroll and happen upon this set of cords. Reviews are good, price is right, they look nice, let’s effin goooo!!!  I buy the cords, they ship as expected and I receive them in a timely manner. Take them out of the package, they look nice, feel durable, appear to be well made. I give them to the wife, she thanks me, and everything is as it should be with the world.  Jump ahead a couple of days, wife says that the cord that I bought for her isn’t working and hasn’t worked at all since she initially tried it out. That’s odd, I think.  So I grab the cord in question and give it a quick once  over. Check out one end, seems fine. Examine the length of the braided jacketing, it checks out. But when I get to the other end to check the jack it seems a little bit wiggly.  well wouldn’t you know that the end just popped right out at the solder joints. This can happen. Rapid manufacturer et. al. mistakes can happen that are difficult to see in QC.  No big deal. I tell her to just grab the other cord and use it. She says that she already had taken it and it too does not work. I figure that is very unlikely and just anomalous. So i take the 2nd cord, inspect it to make sure that everything is intact (which is the case) and decide to try it out on my own Macbook Pro.  So I plug one end into my power supply and the other into the Macbook Pro aaaand it simply does not charge it.  I know that Macs can be picky, especially as it pertains to oem peripherals but honestly, current will flow when a proper connection is made and will not flow when a proper connection is not made. ezpz physics. For whatever reason, with these cords the proper connections were not made and in the end neither cord could be used to charge either Macbook Pro.  Was it just bad luck or did I buy and get sent garbage? I dunno. I do know that I can not recommend purchasing these cords unless you have a very very strong urge to throw something away and you hate your money so much that you will spend it on anything at all just to get rid of it. Though that seems pretty uncommon.At least it didn’t get a 1 star review, right? That would have been just terrible.

They put up with plenty of abuse from my daughter resting the full weight of her iPad on the cable for hours at a time. I like the LED indicating when the cable is providing power to a device. The only thing that I do NOT like is that the E-Marker (internal chip that is required for cables that support the 100W rating for these cables) report that these cables are USB 3.2 Gen 2 cables. Which they are not. They are missing the Rx and Tx pins that make these any type of USB 3 cable. So while they work great for charging, the E-Marker data should be corrected to properly reflect the cable specification. The cables are properly advertised on Amazon as having USB 2.0 data speeds, so I am still giving them a 5-star rating.

reviewTitle: This is likely a 5A/100W charging cable. Voltage drop and cable resistance are plausibly in spec.
reviewDescription: Section 4.4.1 of the USB-C Cable and Connector Specification states that the maximum permissible IR voltage drop on Vbus and GND shall not exceed 500 mV and 250 mV, respectively. Therefore, at 5A drawn on Vbus, its resistance must not exceed 100 milliohms, and GND must not exceed 50 milliohms.The measured (4-wire Kelvin) resistance values for Vbus and GND are approximately 85 milliohms and 65 milliohms, which are both plausibly compliant with the specification given connector mating variability, and in any case do not exceed a total of 150 milliohms.One star deducted for some specimens measuring over 150 milliohms.

So after this test I proceeded to test with a PD65 charger I have for a laptop dock station and the INIU cable worked there in the PD65 charger (it both charged and and turned on the led indicator). The ironical part the I found on this test and cable swapping is that the cable that came with the PD65 charger worked with the Warp65 charger with both Warp65 protocol on the 8T and Warp30 protocol on the 7T. So Oneplus user, if you are looking for a cable that does work with Warp charging protocol (65 and/or 30) then keep looking elsewhere or buy the OG (read your Warp65 block output capabilities and you will be fine) .For other non-Oneplus users, at least it works as intended on a PD charger, will update later if I encounter any problems. I like the firmness and sturdiness of the cable and the led indicator. But for those who like to play landscape game, I would recommend that you get the ones with the 90 degree angle (INIU sells them too)
